we'd clear 600 billion dollars per annum.

259
00:15:56,708 --> 00:15:58,875
In other words, every second

260
00:15:58,958 --> 00:16:01,667
that law is in existence,
we are hemorrhaging money.

261
00:16:01,750 --> 00:16:02,833
What do you want me to do?

262
00:16:02,917 --> 00:16:05,167
We've thrown cash at senators
at both sides of the aisle.

263
00:16:05,250 --> 00:16:06,333
Nobody's budging.

264
00:16:06,417 --> 00:16:08,417
They don't want to vote
against their constituents.

265
00:16:08,458 --> 00:16:11,542
So unless we sway public opinion,
the battle's lost.

266
00:16:11,625 --> 00:16:13,542
Now, to that effect,

267
00:16:13,625 --> 00:16:15,250
my team have come up with

268
00:16:15,333 --> 00:16:18,083
a pretty aggressive new campaign.

269
00:16:18,167 --> 00:16:20,875
Wow factor off-the-charts.

270
00:16:20,958 --> 00:16:22,918
We need to give Americans
a product they can love.

271
00:16:23,917 --> 00:16:25,625
A figure they can rally behind.

272
00:16:25,708 --> 00:16:27,542
Sir, I have dissected this bill.

273
00:16:27,625 --> 00:16:29,083
There are no loopholes.

274
00:16:29,167 --> 00:16:30,601
We can't put a machine on the streets.

275
00:16:30,625 --> 00:16:31,667
Forget machines.

276
00:16:31,750 --> 00:16:33,792
You saw the polls.

277
00:16:33,875 --> 00:16:35,833
Americans don't want a machine.

278
00:16:37,458 --> 00:16:38,958
They want

279
00:16:39,042 --> 00:16:41,458
a product with a conscience.

280
00:16:42,500 --> 00:16:43,500
They want...

281
00:16:44,542 --> 00:16:46,250
something that knows...

282
00:16:48,458 --> 00:16:49,833
what it feels like...

283
00:16:50,917 --> 00:16:51,917
to be human.

284
00:16:58,958 --> 00:17:00,833
We're gonna put a man inside a machine.

285
00:17:05,083 --> 00:17:06,125
You're not you

286
00:17:06,208 --> 00:17:08,917
because of your legs,
your arms, your hands.

287
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:10,583
You're you because of your brain.

288
00:17:10,667 --> 00:17:12,833
It's your brain's capacity

289
00:17:12,917 --> 00:17:15,208
to process information
that makes you who you are.

290
00:17:16,667 --> 00:17:19,458
Relax, and just do
what you've always done.

291
00:17:24,708 --> 00:17:26,667
I've never played with these.

292
00:17:26,750 --> 00:17:28,042
The music doesn't come

293
00:17:28,125 --> 00:17:31,000
from your fingers, Michael,
it comes from your mind.

294
00:17:31,083 --> 00:17:32,833
All you have to do is let it out.

295
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:35,000
Please.

296
00:18:06,125 --> 00:18:07,208
Oh, my God.

297
00:18:11,667 --> 00:18:13,208
No, it's okay. Easy.

298
00:18:15,792 --> 00:18:17,125
His emotions are peaking.

299
00:18:17,208 --> 00:18:18,476
The readings are getting clouded.

300
00:18:18,500 --> 00:18:19,958
It's okay.

301
00:18:20,042 --> 00:18:22,542
Relax. If you get too emotional,

302
00:18:22,625 --> 00:18:24,583
it'll change the chemistry in your brain.

303
00:18:24,667 --> 00:18:25,833
It'll throw the system out.

304
00:18:29,500 --> 00:18:31,583
You're doing great. Come on.

305
00:18:46,667 --> 00:18:47,958
I need emotion to play.

306
00:18:49,333 --> 00:18:51,833
<i>Concierto de Aranjuez,</i>
second movement.

307
00:18:52,833 --> 00:18:54,208
Beautiful piece.

308
00:18:54,292 --> 00:18:57,417
Dennett, when you have
a moment. Thank you.

309
00:18:57,500 --> 00:19:00,542
Now, we agreed on this
a long time ago, Raymond.

310
00:19:00,625 --> 00:19:02,417
I-I wouldn't be asked

311
00:19:02,500 --> 00:19:04,375
to develop combat applications.

312
00:19:04,458 --> 00:19:05,875
My-my work here

313
00:19:05,958 --> 00:19:07,667
is driven by its own questions.

314
00:19:07,750 --> 00:19:09,000
And your work is brilliant.

315
00:19:09,083 --> 00:19:11,208
But your ideas are being underutilized.

316
00:19:11,292 --> 00:19:14,250
Look, I think I found a way

317
00:19:14,333 --> 00:19:17,583
to put real revenue stream
behind your research

318
00:19:17,667 --> 00:19:21,083
and save thousands
of lives in the process.

319
00:19:34,500 --> 00:19:35,750
You're not keeping up your end,

320
00:19:35,833 --> 00:19:37,375
leaving me exposed like that.

321
00:19:37,458 --> 00:19:39,333
Detective Murphy's
just a little impulsive.

322
00:19:39,417 --> 00:19:41,559
So put him on the payroll.
Why are we talkin' about this?

323
00:19:41,583 --> 00:19:43,463
It won't work.
And now that his partner got hit,

324
00:19:43,542 --> 00:19:45,375
he's never gonna let it go.

325
00:19:45,458 --> 00:19:47,417
- What is that?
- Lewis' hospital.

326
00:19:47,500 --> 00:19:49,208
Alex is dropping by this afternoon,

327
00:19:49,292 --> 00:19:50,612
in case you want to send flowers.

328
00:19:55,208 --> 00:19:56,208
Yeah.

329
00:19:56,542 --> 00:19:57,875
I kill a cop,

330
00:19:57,958 --> 00:20:00,042
lookin' over my shoulder
the rest of my life.

331
00:20:00,125 --> 00:20:01,875
That's not good for business.

332
00:20:01,958 --> 00:20:03,758
Who do you think's
gonna be investigating you?

333
00:20:10,292 --> 00:20:12,125
I'm gonna go hard after Lake and Daniels.

334
00:20:14,958 --> 00:20:16,998
I'm gonna have 'em in
bracelets within a month, man.

335
00:20:19,167 --> 00:20:20,647
Hey, Vallon,
I'm walking up right now.

336
00:20:21,875 --> 00:20:22,875
Cameras off?

337
00:20:24,625 --> 00:20:25,625
Clear.

338
00:20:27,250 --> 00:20:30,083
<i>You were right.
We should've had backup.</i>

339
00:20:30,667 --> 00:20:31,667
<i>I'm sorry.</i>

340
00:20:35,750 --> 00:20:37,150
You're not really sleeping, are ya?

341
00:20:40,250 --> 00:20:41,250
Asshole.

342
00:20:43,625 --> 00:20:48,042
Sergeant Thomas Ryan, NYPD.
Paralyzed from the waist down.

343
00:20:49,167 --> 00:20:52,917
He has let himself go
a little since the accident.

344
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:54,250
Pass.

345
00:20:54,333 --> 00:20:55,792
Yeah. Yeah, fair enough.

346
00:20:56,417 --> 00:20:58,958
Officer Alfred Miller, Denver.

347
00:20:59,042 --> 00:21:02,500
"Severe Cerebellar..."

348
00:21:02,583 --> 00:21:04,292
Cerebellar ataxia.

349
00:21:04,375 --> 00:21:06,292
That's why you're the doctor, Doctor.

350
00:21:06,750 --> 00:21:10,167
He scored through the roof
with our urban demos.

351
00:21:10,250 --> 00:21:12,010
Let's keep this one in mind.
I like this guy.

352
00:21:12,042 --> 00:21:14,625
Very good, sir. I saved the best for last.

353
00:21:16,500 --> 00:21:18,583
I give you Sergeant Jack Freeman,

354
00:21:18,667 --> 00:21:20,167
masculinity incarnate.

355
00:21:20,250 --> 00:21:22,792
Led Pittsburgh SWAT for five years,

356
00:21:22,875 --> 00:21:25,083
now confined to a wheelchair.

357
00:21:25,625 --> 00:21:27,500
I...

358
00:21:27,583 --> 00:21:29,792
think I can see the appeal.

359
00:21:29,875 --> 00:21:30,875
No.

360
00:21:30,958 --> 00:21:32,833
What? Why?

361
00:21:32,917 --> 00:21:35,708
Well, check the psych evaluation.
He's far too unstable.

362
00:21:36,042 --> 00:21:37,667
He's trying to say that he has a temper.

363
00:21:38,167 --> 00:21:40,458
Have you any idea
what we'd be putting him through?

364
00:21:40,542 --> 00:21:42,000
The psychological strain

365
00:21:42,083 --> 00:21:43,750
requires someone emotionally balanced.

366
00:21:43,833 --> 00:21:46,250
We have to be scientific.

367
00:21:46,333 --> 00:21:49,000
I mean, we're not selling
a soft drink here, are we?

368
00:21:49,083 --> 00:21:51,542
He's right. Okay. Keep looking.

369
00:21:53,708 --> 00:21:56,500
David, what did I say?
Not until you're finished.

370
00:21:56,583 --> 00:21:58,958
- Hey, guys.
- Hi, Dad.

371
00:21:59,042 --> 00:22:01,750
- Hey.
- Hey, little monkey.

372
00:22:06,083 --> 00:22:07,208
How's the game, buddy?

373
00:22:07,292 --> 00:22:08,542
Damon got ejected,

374
00:22:08,625 --> 00:22:10,250
but we got a two-man advantage.

375
00:22:10,333 --> 00:22:13,042
Oh, yeah? That's fantastic.

376
00:22:13,125 --> 00:22:14,958
Hey, D, why don't you head upstairs

377
00:22:15,042 --> 00:22:16,750
and start getting ready for bed.

378
00:22:16,833 --> 00:22:18,208
But he just got home.

379
00:22:18,917 --> 00:22:20,542
I'll be up in a second.

380
00:22:20,625 --> 00:22:22,958
Tuck you in, okay? All right?

381
00:22:27,042 --> 00:22:28,809
- Now give your mom a kiss.
- Good night, baby.

382
00:22:28,833 --> 00:22:29,833
Too slow, boy.

383
00:22:32,125 --> 00:22:33,208
You're just too slow.

384
00:22:41,708 --> 00:22:43,208
How's Jack holding up?

385
00:22:43,292 --> 00:22:45,012
They said a week
till he's back on his feet.

386
00:22:46,292 --> 00:22:47,292
It's my fault.

387
00:22:47,375 --> 00:22:48,735
We shouldn't even have been there.

388
00:22:51,958 --> 00:22:52,958
Here.

389
00:23:56,542 --> 00:23:57,875
Oh, shit, I thought I fixed that.

390
00:23:58,417 --> 00:23:59,458
It'll stop.

391
00:24:06,125 --> 00:24:07,500
It's gonna wake up David.

392
00:24:51,667 --> 00:24:52,833
<i>He suffered</i>

393
00:24:52,917 --> 00:24:56,167
<i>fourth-degree burns
over 80 percent of his body.</i>

394
00:24:56,625 --> 00:24:58,583
<i>Lower spine has been severed.</i>

395
00:25:00,042 --> 00:25:01,375
<i>If he survives...</i>

396
00:25:02,667 --> 00:25:03,958
he'll be paralyzed

397
00:25:04,042 --> 00:25:06,083
from the waist down
and confined to a wheelchair.

398
00:25:09,458 --> 00:25:10,833
Mrs. Murphy...

399
00:25:12,792 --> 00:25:14,750
we don't have to do this.

400
00:25:16,625 --> 00:25:19,250
I need to know everything
before I make a decision.

401
00:25:22,792 --> 00:25:24,042
Please continue.

402
00:25:25,333 --> 00:25:27,542
Vestibulocochlear,

403
00:25:27,625 --> 00:25:30,417
optical nerves have
been critically damaged.

404
00:25:31,750 --> 00:25:33,375
He'll be blind in one eye.

405
00:25:34,458 --> 00:25:35,500
Most likely deaf.

406
00:25:36,958 --> 00:25:39,083
Frankly, Dr. Norton
and the Omni Foundation

407
00:25:39,167 --> 00:25:40,833
are the leaders in this field.

408
00:25:40,917 --> 00:25:44,583
In my opinion, this is
the only chance your husband has.

409
00:25:44,667 --> 00:25:46,500
I'd seriously consider their offer.

410
00:25:49,625 --> 00:25:50,833
I'm sorry, Doctor.

411
00:25:52,708 --> 00:25:54,125
I need time to think.

412
00:25:54,208 --> 00:25:55,625
I'm afraid, Mrs. Murphy,

413
00:25:55,708 --> 00:25:57,625
time is one thing you don't have.

414
00:26:02,375 --> 00:26:04,542
You say you can save him,
but what does that mean?

415
00:26:08,250 --> 00:26:09,917
What kind of life will he have?

416
00:26:27,292 --> 00:26:29,750
- Thanks.
- Thanks, buddy.

417
00:26:29,833 --> 00:26:31,625
You know she's gonna make me dance again.

418
00:26:31,708 --> 00:26:33,458
Now that I've gotta see.

419
00:26:33,542 --> 00:26:34,622
You don't want to see that.

420
00:26:34,667 --> 00:26:35,708
Here she comes now.

421
00:26:36,458 --> 00:26:37,458
Hold on to that.

422
00:26:37,542 --> 00:26:38,750
Get out there, partner.

423
00:26:40,458 --> 00:26:41,833
Every time.

424
00:26:45,917 --> 00:26:47,125
Get her, boy.

425
00:27:05,625 --> 00:27:07,333
Subject is still dreaming.

426
00:27:08,708 --> 00:27:10,458
He's retrieving memories,

427
00:27:10,542 --> 00:27:13,250
trying to make sense of
sensorial stimulation package 37.

428
00:27:14,833 --> 00:27:15,833
Perfect, Kim.

429
00:27:17,875 --> 00:27:19,292
Let's reconnect the spine.

430
00:27:20,875 --> 00:27:21,958
Time to wake him up.

431
00:27:48,833 --> 00:27:49,875
Excuse me?

432
00:27:51,042 --> 00:27:52,125
What are you doing here?

433
00:27:52,875 --> 00:27:53,875
Baby, where you going?

434
00:27:57,792 --> 00:27:58,792
Lewis.

435
00:28:09,958 --> 00:28:12,542
Subject regaining cognitive functions.

436
00:28:14,625 --> 00:28:15,667
What's happening?

437
00:28:18,500 --> 00:28:19,500
Where am I?

438
00:28:19,542 --> 00:28:21,333
You were in an explosion, Alex.

439
00:28:22,042 --> 00:28:23,750
You're in a hospital.

440
00:28:24,208 --> 00:28:25,208
Where's...

441
00:28:26,625 --> 00:28:29,125
Where's Ciara? My wife. Where's my wife?

442
00:28:29,208 --> 00:28:31,458
I want you to calm down,
Alex. Listen to me.

443
00:28:31,542 --> 00:28:33,417
You're okay. And your family's fine.

444
00:28:33,500 --> 00:28:34,833
Both your wife and your son.

445
00:28:36,125 --> 00:28:37,583
Who the hell are you?

446
00:28:37,667 --> 00:28:40,292
I'm Dr. Dennett Norton. I'm treating you.

447
00:28:41,042 --> 00:28:42,042
Heart rate rising.

448
00:28:45,250 --> 00:28:46,250
I can't move.

449
00:28:49,458 --> 00:28:51,792
I can't move. What the hell is all that?

450
00:28:51,875 --> 00:28:53,167
Visual input unstable.

451
00:28:53,250 --> 00:28:54,792
I want you to relax, Alex.

452
00:28:54,875 --> 00:28:56,184
Subject's dumping too much epinephrine.

453
00:28:56,208 --> 00:28:57,448
- Should we purge it?
- Not yet.

454
00:28:58,292 --> 00:28:59,667
Unlock vertebrae.

455
00:29:05,208 --> 00:29:07,000
Go ahead, Kim.

456
00:29:07,083 --> 00:29:09,833
Unlock upper, lower extremities.

457
00:29:22,917 --> 00:29:24,917
What kind of suit is this?

458
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:28,333
It's not a suit, Alex. It's...

459
00:29:30,500 --> 00:29:31,792
It's you.

460
00:29:33,708 --> 00:29:35,667
This was the only option.

461
00:29:35,750 --> 00:29:39,333
We're here, all of us,
to make you whole again.

462
00:29:39,417 --> 00:29:40,833
Full body unlock.

463
00:29:40,917 --> 00:29:42,958
I want you to walk now, Alex.

464
00:29:43,500 --> 00:29:44,625
You can do that.

465
00:30:09,292 --> 00:30:10,375
This seems so real.

466
00:30:13,750 --> 00:30:15,625
Alex, it's very important

467
00:30:15,708 --> 00:30:17,333
you understand what is happening.

468
00:30:17,417 --> 00:30:18,792
This is real.

469
00:30:18,875 --> 00:30:22,167
It's not a dream,
it's not drugs or anesthetics.

470
00:30:22,250 --> 00:30:25,083
I know I'm dreaming
'cause I can feel all of this.

471
00:30:25,167 --> 00:30:28,125
Alex, amputees can often
feel their missing appendages.

472
00:30:28,208 --> 00:30:29,518
It's called phantom limb sensation.

473
00:30:29,542 --> 00:30:31,292
What do you mean "amputees"?

474
00:30:31,375 --> 00:30:33,309
- What the hell did you do to me?
- You need to relax.

475
00:30:33,333 --> 00:30:34,750
Take this off me now.

476
00:30:34,833 --> 00:30:37,542
I need to get out of this thing.
What did you do to me?

477
00:30:37,625 --> 00:30:39,750
What have you done to me?

478
00:30:39,833 --> 00:30:41,625
Alex? Hey!

479
00:30:43,125 --> 00:30:44,250
Shut him down.

480
00:30:44,333 --> 00:30:46,542
No! Let him run! Let him run!

481
00:31:07,542 --> 00:31:08,542
Where am I?

482
00:31:33,250 --> 00:31:34,583
<i>Alex, please.</i>

483
00:31:36,458 --> 00:31:37,458
<i>Stop.</i>

484
00:31:38,625 --> 00:31:40,042
<i>Alex, you have to stop.</i>

485
00:31:41,667 --> 00:31:42,708
<i>Please.</i>

486
00:31:44,083 --> 00:31:45,083
<i>Alex.</i>

487
00:31:46,667 --> 00:31:47,833
Please stop.

488
00:31:48,625 --> 00:31:50,292
Stay where you are

489
00:31:50,375 --> 00:31:52,667
and we'll come and pick you up.

490
00:32:26,583 --> 00:32:27,833
Okay, Kim.

491
00:32:29,458 --> 00:32:30,667
Shut him down.

492
00:32:56,500 --> 00:32:57,500
Alex...

493
00:32:58,792 --> 00:33:00,375
you can't run from this.

494
00:33:02,833 --> 00:33:06,417
You have to understand
the reality of the situation.

495
00:33:10,292 --> 00:33:11,292
Show me.

496
00:33:13,792 --> 00:33:14,792
Kim.

497
00:33:31,375 --> 00:33:32,375
Oh!

498
00:33:34,792 --> 00:33:35,792
No.

499
00:33:39,958 --> 00:33:40,958
Holy Christ.

500
00:33:42,333 --> 00:33:43,792
Holy Christ.

501
00:33:46,250 --> 00:33:47,833
Holy Christ, there's nothing left.

502
00:33:54,500 --> 00:33:57,917
Your body may have gone,
but you're still here.

503
00:34:04,667 --> 00:34:06,417
That's not even my brain.

504
00:34:06,500 --> 00:34:09,792
We had to repair the damaged areas.

505
00:34:09,875 --> 00:34:12,292
But we didn't interfere with
your emotion or your intellect.

506
00:34:12,375 --> 00:34:15,042
Do you understand me, Alex?

507
00:34:16,375 --> 00:34:18,833
You're... You're in control.

508
00:34:19,667 --> 00:34:21,833
- I'm in control?
- Yes.

509
00:34:24,875 --> 00:34:25,875
Okay.

510
00:34:29,458 --> 00:34:30,583
If I'm in control...

511
00:34:33,083 --> 00:34:34,292
then I wanna die.

512
00:34:36,417 --> 00:34:38,167
Just unplug whatever it is

513
00:34:38,250 --> 00:34:41,375
keepin' me alive and end this nightmare.

514
00:34:42,125 --> 00:34:43,667
Now, say I did that,

515
00:34:43,750 --> 00:34:46,583
which as a doctor would
almost be impossible for me,

516
00:34:46,667 --> 00:34:48,083
but say I did.

517
00:34:50,750 --> 00:34:52,250
What do I say to your wife?

518
00:34:53,542 --> 00:34:55,208
What does she say to your son?

519
00:34:55,292 --> 00:34:57,833
That it didn't work. That you tried.

520
00:34:58,875 --> 00:35:00,208
Somethin' went wrong.

521
00:35:01,625 --> 00:35:03,083
You did everything you could...

522
00:35:07,333 --> 00:35:08,833
but I died.

523
00:35:08,917 --> 00:35:11,000
So after all they've been through,

524
00:35:11,083 --> 00:35:14,542
all the pain, all their hope restored,

525
00:35:14,625 --> 00:35:15,958
we would just rip that away?

526
00:35:18,083 --> 00:35:20,125
Your wife loves you, Alex.

527
00:35:20,208 --> 00:35:22,708
She signed the consent forms herself.

528
00:35:22,792 --> 00:35:25,375
Otherwise, you couldn't
